INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (44,1,'2010-03-31 14:25:09','2010-03-31 13:25:09','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">\r\n&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application. (Pro. ASP.Net 3.5)</blockquote>\r\n\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\nCurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()\r\n</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-9','','','2010-03-31 14:25:09','2010-03-31 13:25:09','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (45,1,'2010-04-08 17:37:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<strong>Mocks</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>A mock is an object that mimics another object for the purpose of testing <strong>and </strong>allows you to verify how it was used by setting expectations and verifying them later. It is a kind of <strong>Test Double</strong> (like a move double) with behaviour verification (as opposed to state verification which stubs may do).\r\n\r\n<strong>Stubs</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>A stub is a test double that is used to \"provide canned answers to calls made during the test\" (<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html</a>). It deals with state, not behaviour, and is used in place of aÂ <em>real</em> object to help isolate the test from real objects.\r\n\r\n<strong>AutoMockingContainer</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using an AutoMockingContainer which, given a type, creates a mocked object of that type. The really useful thing is it will satisfy all dependencies for that type <strong>auto</strong>matically.</span></strong>\r\n\r\nUsage of our AutoMockingContainer implementation is simple:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Call Create&lt;T&gt;() to get the object under test</li>\r\n	<li>Call Get&lt;T&gt;() to get a mocked object</li>\r\n	<li>Set expectations on mocked object, act on object under test, verify expectations on mocked object</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>MvcContrib.TestHelper</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">MvcContrib contains some helper methods</span> </strong>specifically for MVC controller testing. More information here: <a href=\"http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html\">http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Rhino.Mocks</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using the MockRepository object to create my stubs. </span></strong></span></strong>','Unit Testing Controllers with Mocks and Stubs','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-04-08 17:37:58','2010-04-08 16:37:58','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=45',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (46,1,'2010-04-08 15:08:27','2010-04-08 14:08:27','<strong>Mocks</strong>\nA mock is an object that mimics another object for the purpose of testing <strong>and </strong>allows you to verify how it was used by setting expectations and verifying them later. It is a kind of <strong>Test Double</strong> (like a move double) with behaviour verification (as opposed to state verification which stubs may do).\n\n<strong>Stubs</strong>\nA stub is a test double that is used to \"provide canned answers to calls made during the test\" (<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html</a>). It deals with state, not behaviour, and is used in place of aÂ <em>real</em> object to help isolate the test from real objects.\n\nRhino Mocks\n\n<strong>AutoMockingContainer</strong>\nI\'m using an AutoMockingContainer which, given a type, creates a mocked object of that type. The really useful thing is it will satisfy all dependencies for that type <strong>auto</strong>matically.\n\nUsage of our AutoMockingContainer implementation is simple:\n<ul>\n	<li>Call Create&lt;T&gt;() to get the object under test</li>\n	<li>Call Get&lt;T&gt;() to get a mocked object</li>\n	<li>Set expectations on mocked object, act on object under test, verify expectations on mocked object</li>\n</ul>','','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision','','','2010-04-08 15:08:27','2010-04-08 14:08:27','',45,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/08/45-revision/',0,'revision','',0);
